Europe Needs Immigration Restart
Brussels — More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
At the same time, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching for safe harbors throughout the summer where passengers on board could be allowed to disembark.
Refugee and migrant camps on the Greek island of Lesbos are overcrowded, and similar conditions exist in other reception centers in Libya.
Turkey tore up the 2016 agreement that aimed to prevent migrants from entering the EU.
Although Europe wants to help immigrants and respects international law, it does not want to be overcrowded.
In 2015-16, the number of refugees and migrants entering the European Union surged—many of them fleeing the war in Syria—greatly affecting trust within the EU.
The massive influx of immigrants has eroded the government's confidence in managing the EU's external borders and asylum policies, also highlighting the ineffectiveness of cooperation with countries of origin.
As a result, immigration has become a political football, a favorite issue for populists.
Under the leadership of President Ursula von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control of the migration issue while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this reason, the EU needs to revise its guidelines in four areas and mobilize member states to take action in the interest of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping its internal borders open.
Countries where people can freely move internally, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, do not outsource external border control to a particular state or region.
Controlling the external borders of the EU is both a collective task and a national responsibility.
The European Border and Coast Guard Agency, Frontex, must be further strengthened and should deploy joint task forces with member states — including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal migration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to handle economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Treating them as one and the same has brought the asylum system close to collapse; addressing them separately helps ensure that immigrants fearing for their lives can voice their concerns while their rights are protected.
Addressing the real economic and social needs of the European Union requires an effective Blue Card or Green Card policy targeting economic migrants, along with the implementation of an overall immigration target.
Such a massive volume of information cannot be dealt with by waiting until the next immigration crisis to consider introducing these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic immigrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Secondly, policies must clearly define which immigrants are desirable.
Third, member states must specify what EU assistance is needed to ensure a smooth immigration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be brought to the forefront to facilitate the return of undocumented immigrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, member states are responsible for managing immigration from outside the EU themselves.
However, if the government reaches an agreement on the overall EU immigration target, it will be a significant progress.
In return, member states can specify the countries of origin and specific requirements for economic immigrants they wish to accept, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
In this way, the right to accept immigrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long implemented an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skill level, and age.
Europe can do this as well.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First of all, the one-size-fits-all requirement of compulsorily distributing asylum seekers within the EU must be abandoned.
This demand undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if the border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective.
Furthermore, it is not possible to expect the EU's frontline member states to solve the issue of illegal immigration crossing external borders on their own.
The refugee camps are already overcrowded, and the immigrants are subjected to abuse by the authorities or driven northward.
The responsibility of the first Member State reached by the migrant must be complemented by EU solidarity.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to streamline the operations and management capabilities of national asylum agencies.
Only in this way can the decisions of the state be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
After streamlining the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum institutions, the asylum application processing procedures can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should establish stronger mutually beneficial cooperation with countries of origin and transit countries.
These connections are crucial for repatriating immigrants who are legally prohibited from entering the European Union.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all its foreign policy instruments, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in areas such as security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's immigration targets, along with skills cooperation aimed at preparing for European job markets, can offer third countries seeking stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes population explosions in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a shortage of job opportunities.
The EU's assistance should focus on restoring stability and reducing risks through support for security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area can make investments safer, unleash private and domestic finance, thereby enabling national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternative options for immigration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to steer the EU away from instinctive reactions to the migration crisis and move towards a more coherent and sustainable approach, both internally and externally.
We must never miss the opportunity.
